"Of course, Sweetie. Have fun."\r\u003cbr\u003e(Here's one tip to bedwetters or parents of bedwetters: have a codeword or phrase. It was settled. I would be sleeping in the same living room as Heather and eight other girls.\r\u003cbr\u003eThe anxiety of the impending night took over. I felt like a zombie, going through the motions of a child at play. I didn't bring my own pyjamas or linens, so Mrs Peters provided me a sleeping bag and a pair of pyjamas. I lie, motionless, in panic and urine, for what seems like hours before the other girls start to wake up. I do the only thing a terrified zombie can do: I pretend it didn't happen. To still be a bedwetter in high school, to have a condition this deeply entrenched, is a pretty serious problem for a child.\r\u003cbr\u003eI was elected student leader of our school's annual camping trip, which I was proud of but extremely nervous and anxious about for a couple of reasons: 1) I was a bedwetter. This is going to be tricky, and 2) did I mention I pee in my sleep?!\r\u003cbr\u003eIn the last month of my 12th year, my mother helped me hide 3 diapers in the bottom of my sleeping bag and sent me off to go lead my fellow students camping. When we got there, we lifted our gigantic packs on to our backs and up the mountain we hiked, led by me. .\r\u003cbr\u003eAs we set up our tents it started to pour, and after eating our smoky, fire-burned dinner, we went to sleep. Surrounded by my tentmates, I subtly reached to the bottom of my sleeping bag with my toes and put on my diaper without incident, probably because, in their wildest dreams, among the giggling and gossip and talking about boys they would never guess that one of us was wearing Pampers.\r\u003cbr\u003eOur bus pulled into the school parking lot after our long journey. It filled me with a loneliness that only deepened when I was not alone.\r\u003cbr\u003eMy parents sent me to a therapist.
